\section{Characterisation of open sets in $\R$}

Here are two solutions. The first is the one Alex and I knew before
speaking to Prof. McMullen a couple of days ago, and is the one we
hinted at if you came to office hours or section. The second is (I
believe) the one Prof. McMullen had in mind, which is a bit cleaner
(sorry for the suboptimal hinting!).

\subsection{Existence via equivalence relation}

For $x,y \in U$ write $x \sim y$ if and only if there exists an open
interval $I \subseteq U$ such that $x, y \in I$. We show $\sim$ is an
equivalence relation.
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Reflexivity.} Let $x \in U$. Since the open intervals
  form a basis for the topology on $\R$ (and $U$ is open) we can find
  an open interval $I \subseteq U$ with $x \in I$. So $x \sim x$.
\item \textit{Symmetry.} Tautological.
\item \textit{Transitivity.} Let $x,y,z \in U$ such that $x \sim y$
  and $y \sim z$. By definition there are open intervals $I,J
  \subseteq U$ such that $x,y \in I$ and $y,z \in J$. Since $y \in I
  \cap J$ and $x,z \in I \cup J$, we have $x \sim z$ by the following
  lemma.
\end{itemize}

\begin{lemma}
  \label{interval-union}
  Let $I,J \subseteq \R$ open intervals with $I \cap J \ne
  \emptyset$. Then $I \cup J$ is an open interval.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Write $I =: (a_1,b_1)$ and $J =: (a_2,b_2)$, and without loss of
  generality $a_1 \le a_2$. Since $I \cap J \ne \emptyset$, we must
  have $b_1 > a_2$. It follows that $I \cup J = (a_1, \max(b_1,b_2))$.
\end{proof}

Now let $x \in U$ and let $U_x := \{y \in U \mid x \sim y\}$ its
equivalence class. We claim $U_x = (a, b)$ where $a := \inf U_x$ and
$b := \sup U_x$ (where we allow $a = -\infty$ and $b = \infty$).

Let $y \in (a, b)$. Suppose $y < x$. By definition of $\inf$ we can
choose $a' \in (a, y) \cap U_x$. Thus there exists an open interval $I
\subseteq U$ such that $a', x \in I$. But then $a' < y < x \implies
y \in I$, so $y \in I$ and thus $y \in U_x$. We have a symmetric
argument when $y > x$, and of course $x \in U_x$, so $(a, b) \subseteq
U_x$.

By definition of $\inf$ and $\sup$ it only remains to be shown that
$a,b \notin U_x$. Assume $a \in U_x$. Then there exists an open
interval $I \subseteq U$ such that $a,x \in I$. Since $I$ is open
there must exist $a' \in I \cap (-\infty, a)$. But then $a' \in U_x$,
contradicting that $a = \inf U_x$. A symmetric argument shows $b
\notin U_x$, and hence $U_x = (a,b)$.

Then observe that $U$ is partitioned into disjoint sets by the
equivalence classes $\{U_x\}_{x \in U}$, each of which we have shown
is an open interval.

\subsection{Existence via maximal intervals}

For $x \in U$ define:
\begin{itemize}
\item $a_x := \inf \{a \in \R \mid (a,x] \subseteq U\}$;
\item $b_x := \sup \{b \in \R \mid [x,b) \subseteq U\}$;
\item $I_x := (a_x, b_x)$.
\end{itemize}
Note the above are well-defined because $U$ is open and hence there
exists an open interval $I \subseteq U$ with $x \in U$. By definition
of $\inf$ and $\sup$ we have $I_x \subseteq U$, and of course $x \in
U$. Thus $U = \bigcup_{x \in U} I_x$. We need only show then that if
$y \in U - I_x$ then $I_x \cap I_y = \emptyset$. Assume the
contrary. By Lemma~\ref{interval-union}, $I_x \cup I_y = (a,b)$. Since
$y \in I_y - I_x$ we must have either $a < a_x$ or $b > b_x$, but this
contradicts the definitions of $a_x, b_x$.

\subsection{Uniqueness}

Suppose $U = \coprod_{\alpha \in A} I_\alpha = \coprod_{\beta \in B}
J_\beta$ are two decompositions of $U$ into disjoint open
intervals. We want that $\{I_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A} =
\{J_\beta\}_{\beta \in B}$; by symmetry it suffices to show for each
$\alpha \in A$ there exists $\beta \in B$ such that $J_\beta =
I_\alpha$. So let $\alpha \in A$, and let $I_\alpha =: (a,b)$. Let $x
\in (a,b)$; since $x \in U$ we can pick $\beta \in B$ such that $x \in
J_\beta =: (c,d)$. Then $(a,b) \cap (c,d) \ne \emptyset$, whence
either $a \in (c,d)$ or $c \in (a,b)$. In the first case, $a \in U
\implies a \in I_{\alpha'}$ for some $\alpha' \in A - \{\alpha\}$. But
then since $I_{\alpha'}$ is open we must have $I_{\alpha'} \cap
I_\alpha \ne \emptyset$, contradicting disjointness. The second case
is treated in the same way.

\begin{remark}
  Note that uniqueness is not immediate from either of the above
  proofs for existence, as far as I can tell.\footnote{If I am being
    dumb and it actually is immediate, come convince me and I'll fix
    my grading.} In particular for the proof via equivalence relation,
  it's not a priori clear that any decomposition into disjoint
  intervals must precisely agree with the decomposition under the
  defined equivalence relation.
\end{remark}

